    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "wait what? why are you talking about goblins lol. i was asking for a physics explanation. can you just explain it without the weird stories and just stick to the actual science/mechanics of it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the confusion. Quantum entanglement is a physical phenomenon that occurs when pairs or groups of particles interact in ways such that the quantum state of each particle cannot be described independently of the state of the others, even when the particles are separated by large distances. This means that the properties of one particle are directly related to the properties of another, no matter how far apart they are. This connection persists instantaneously, defying classical intuitions about the separability of distant objects.\n\nIn contrast, classical correlation refers to the predictable relationship between two variables that are not necessarily quantumly entangled. For example, if you flip a coin and it lands on heads, you can predict that the other coin will land on tails. This correlation is due to the coins being separate objects with no direct, instantaneous connection. In classical physics, information cannot travel faster than the speed of light, so any correlation between distant objects is mediated by some physical process, such as light or sound waves, which takes time to propagate.\n\nQuantum entanglement, therefore, represents a fundamental departure from classical physics, challenging our understanding of locality and causality. It has been experimentally confirmed and is a key resource in emerging technologies like quantum computing and quantum cryptography.",
      "source": "target",
